(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(appendix
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :letter              "H"
  :title               "Save Slots and world/snapshot"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"Two save systems. Cortex-based (automatic, always on, low-cost) and
snapshot-based (explicit, heavier, captures full runtime state).
Combined, they handle every save requirement a narrative game has.

This appendix covers slot naming, versioning, migration when your
story changes, and the small UX details that make save systems
feel good.

---

## Cortex-based saves: what's automatic

Every `cortex/write` is persistent. Nothing else needed. The player
who closes the game and reopens it a week later sees the same Cortex
state.

That covers:
- past-choices
- inventory
- reputation
- world-state flags
- customer preferences
- everything under state/*, log/*, dialogue-log/*

For most narrative games, this is 90% of what saves need to do.

---

## Snapshot-based saves: what's manual

For the other 10% — animation state, ongoing timers, entity positions
mid-scene, camera position — use `world/snapshot`.

```scheme
(define (save-now slot)
  ;; Cortex is already saved. Snapshot the rest.
  (let ((snap (world/snapshot)))
    (cortex/write (slot-key slot) snap)
    (cortex/write (slot-timestamp slot) (current-timestamp))))

(define (load-now slot)
  (let ((snap (cortex/read (slot-key slot))))
    (when snap
      (world/restore! snap))))
```

`world/snapshot` returns a large blob (kilobytes-to-megabytes) of
the current runtime state. `world/restore!` accepts that blob and
resets the runtime to that state.

Only snapshot when you actually need the mid-scene state saved. For
scene-boundary saves, Cortex is enough.

---

## The three-tier save strategy

Combine three save mechanisms for robust user experience.

### Tier 1: Cortex auto-persist (invisible)

Every scene write happens continuously. The player never thinks
about it. If they crash-quit, everything up to their last write is
preserved.

### Tier 2: Auto-save at chapter boundaries (slot 0)

At every chapter transition, snapshot to slot 0.

```scheme
(define (chapter-transition n)
  (save-now 0)                        ;; auto-slot
  (cortex/write 'current-chapter n)
  (start-chapter n))
```

If the player quits mid-chapter and opens next week, they can
'resume from auto-save' — which returns them to the chapter start,
not the middle of a scene.

### Tier 3: Manual named saves (slots 1-4)

The player explicitly saves via menu.

```scheme
(define (save-menu)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"~ save ~\")
  ;; List slots 1-4 with names + timestamps
  ;; Player presses 1-4 to save
  )
```

Named saves are for the player who wants to branch — 'save here, try
option A, come back if I don't like it.'

Together the three tiers cover: crash resilience (tier 1), casual
resume (tier 2), deliberate branching (tier 3).

---

## Slot design

Reserve slot 0 for auto-save. Offer slots 1-4 for manual. That is
five total. More is over-engineered for most games.

```scheme
(define (all-slots) '(0 1 2 3 4))

(define (slot-key n)
  (string->symbol (string-append \"save/slot/\" (number->string n))))

(define (slot-name n)
  (or (cortex/read
        (string->symbol
          (string-append \"save/slot/\" (number->string n) \"/name\")))
      (case n
        ((0) \"Auto-save\")
        (else (string-append \"Save \" (number->string n))))))

(define (slot-timestamp n)
  (cortex/read
    (string->symbol
      (string-append \"save/slot/\" (number->string n) \"/timestamp\"))))

(define (slot-empty? n)
  (not (cortex/read (slot-key n))))
```

Each slot has three keys: the snapshot, an optional name, a
timestamp. Empty slots have none of these; `slot-empty?` returns #t.

---

## The save menu UX

Show ALL slots including empty ones. The player needs to see the
whole space.

```scheme
(define (save-menu)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 40 40 \"~ save your progress ~\")

  (let loop ((n 0))
    (when (<= n 4)
      (let* ((empty? (slot-empty? n))
             (name (slot-name n))
             (ts (slot-timestamp n))
             (label
              (cond
                (empty? (string-append \"[\" (number->string n) \"] \" name \"  (empty)\"))
                (else   (string-append \"[\" (number->string n) \"] \" name
                                       \"  (\" (ts->prose ts) \")\")))))
        (paint-text 60 (+ 80 (* n 35)) label))
      (loop (+ n 1))))

  (paint-text 40 300 \"[press 0-4 to save into that slot]\")
  (paint-text 40 325 \"[ESC to cancel]\"))
```

Slot 0 (auto-save) is offered too — but it's usually filled and
players usually don't overwrite it. Their choice.

Timestamp prose ('2 hours ago', 'yesterday', '3 days ago') is
friendlier than raw timestamps.

---

## The load menu

Same shape, different action.

```scheme
(define (load-menu)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 40 40 \"~ load a save ~\")

  (let loop ((n 0))
    (when (<= n 4)
      (let* ((empty? (slot-empty? n))
             (name (slot-name n)))
        (paint-text 60 (+ 80 (* n 35))
          (if empty?
              (string-append \"[\" (number->string n) \"] (empty)\")
              (string-append \"[\" (number->string n) \"] \" name))))
      (loop (+ n 1))))

  (paint-text 40 300 \"[press 0-4 to load; ESC to cancel]\"))
```

Do not offer to load empty slots. Grey them out or filter them from
input.

---

## Overwrite confirmation

If a player is about to overwrite an existing save, confirm.

```scheme
(define (save-with-confirm slot)
  (cond
    ((slot-empty? slot)
     (save-now slot))
    (else
     (paint-text 40 400
       (string-append \"[\" (number->string slot) \"] already has \"
                      (slot-name slot) \" — overwrite?\"))
     (paint-text 40 430 \"[Y] yes   [N] no\")
     (on-key
       (lambda (k)
         (case k
           ((y) (save-now slot))
           ((n) (cancel-save))))))))
```

Do NOT confirm for slot 0. Auto-saves overwrite silently — that's
the point.

---

## Naming a save

Let the player type a name for the save.

```scheme
(define (save-with-name slot)
  (paint-text 40 400 \"Name this save (or leave blank for default):\")
  (input/text-buffer 40 430
    :on-submit
    (lambda (name)
      (when (not (empty-string? name))
        (cortex/write
          (string->symbol (string-append \"save/slot/\"
                                         (number->string slot)
                                         \"/name\"))
          name))
      (save-now slot))))
```

Player types 'before the villain reveal' and it becomes the slot's
label. If they type nothing, the default 'Save 1' name is used.

Small feature. Big user value. Named saves are the difference between
5 anonymous slots and 5 memorable moments.

---

## Migration when the story updates

The hardest problem in save systems: your story updates but old
saves point to node ids that no longer exist.

Three strategies.

### Strategy 1: version the save

Every save records the story version at the time of saving.

```scheme
(define (save-now slot)
  (let ((snap (world/snapshot)))
    (cortex/write (slot-key slot) snap)
    (cortex/write (slot-version-key slot) (story-version))))
```

When loading, check version:

```scheme
(define (load-now slot)
  (let ((saved-version (cortex/read (slot-version-key slot)))
        (current-version (story-version)))
    (cond
      ((equal? saved-version current-version)
       (world/restore! (cortex/read (slot-key slot))))
      (else
       (offer-migration slot saved-version)))))
```

If versions differ, migrate.

### Strategy 2: migration functions

For each version pair, write a migration.

```scheme
(define (migrate save-blob from-v to-v)
  (cond
    ((and (equal? from-v \"1.0.0\") (equal? to-v \"1.1.0\"))
     (migrate-1.0-to-1.1 save-blob))
    ;; ... more migration paths ...
    (else
     ;; No migration path — offer to start over.
     save-blob)))

(define (migrate-1.0-to-1.1 blob)
  ;; If node 'kitchen-old was renamed to 'kitchen, rewrite it in the blob.
  ;; If new state flags need default values, set them.
  ;; Return updated blob.
  ...)
```

This is real engineering work. For games that update frequently, it's
worth doing. For a game shipped once and rarely updated, skip.

### Strategy 3: 'restart from chapter' fallback

If migration fails, offer to restart the player from the beginning
of the chapter they were in.

```scheme
(define (offer-restart-chapter slot)
  (let ((chapter (cortex/read 'current-chapter)))
    (paint-text 40 400
      (string-append \"This save is from an older version. Restart\n\"
                     \"chapter \" (number->string chapter)
                     \" from the beginning?\"))
    (paint-text 40 460 \"[Y] restart   [N] cancel\")))
```

Lossy but usable. The player loses mid-chapter progress but keeps
Cortex flags (choices, reputation, inventory).

---

## Cross-device save (advanced)

For players who play on phone and tablet, saves should sync.

`cortex/write` under the hood syncs to the cloud (for logged-in
users) — so Cortex-based saves are automatically cross-device.

`world/snapshot` may or may not sync depending on backend. If your
snapshots are large, they may live only on the local device.

For safest cross-device: rely on Cortex for state; use snapshot only
for one-session ephemeral saves. That is the discipline for cross-
device narrative games.

---

## Summary

Two save systems: Cortex (automatic, always on) and snapshot (manual,
heavier). Three tiers: auto-persist, chapter auto-save, named manual
slots. Five total slots (0-4). Name your saves. Confirm overwrites
(except slot 0). Version your saves for migration.

The player who loves your game will replay it. The player who quits
should be able to come back where they left off. Save systems make
both possible.")
